../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:11:### Step 1 - Freeze one target unknown and one endpoint before algebra begins
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:17:- The endpoint choices are too coarse. "Localized regularity," "continuation criterion," and "concentration exclusion" have very different burdens. A commutator that helps in a continuation criterion may be useless for localization once cutoff commutators and pressure recovery are inserted. Freezing only the endpoint family does not prevent later goalpost shifting.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:44:### Step 4 - Insert the mechanism into one endpoint-facing inequality
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:48:- If the endpoint is localized regularity or concentration exclusion, cutoff commutators and pressure localization are not "cleanup"; they are often the whole game. The chain says to include them immediately, which is good, but it does not acknowledge that this will usually erase any formal commutator gain found in Step 2.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:49:- "Write one explicit inequality" is necessary but insufficient. A line can be explicit and still be useless if it imports a stronger norm than the endpoint can afford. The real question is whether the inequality closes with the regularity class already available, not whether one can symbolically place the commutator into the argument.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:51:- There is a structural mismatch between SQG-style mechanisms and NS endpoint burdens. SQG commutators help because scalar truncation and the active scalar structure align. In 3D NS, even if a commutator appears in reformulated variables, the endpoint burden usually lives in the original vector field, pressure, or vorticity geometry. The chain has not shown that the gain transfers back without restoring the full difficulty.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:53:Fair point in its favor: forcing an endpoint-facing line before declaring victory is exactly right. But given the nature of the route, Step 4 is the most likely graveyard, and the chain does not say that clearly enough.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:92:- It includes an honest obstruction endpoint instead of pretending every branch must produce a positive route.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-02.md:93:- It demands an endpoint-facing insertion rather than stopping at formal algebra.
