../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-007/judgments/chain-03.md:5:The attack is mostly right. The original chain has a real research instinct: it tries to test whether full 3D energy-helicity transport contains theorem-relevant structure that is not visible in energy-only or same-helicity-only viewpoints. That is a legitimate target. But the attack correctly identifies the main danger: the chain treats joint energy-helicity flux as if it were already near a coercive mechanism, when in practice helicity is sign-indefinite, cancellation-prone, and hard to localize.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-007/judgments/chain-03.md:7:The refined version should therefore remain open to a positive route only under a much harder admission standard. The default working hypothesis should be that the exact coupled invariant geometry is non-coercive unless the branch can exhibit one one-sided, localization-stable, endpoint-relevant gain early.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-007/judgments/chain-03.md:14:The attack is right that the original Step 1 froze the endpoint and invariant package too early, and it is right that the package menu was too heterogeneous to treat as a single neutral choice. It is also right that the minimum gain standard needed to name one explicit bad term or exclusion pattern. But some early freezing is still good method. The fix is to freeze guardrails and admissibility standards first, while delaying the final endpoint lock until a candidate one-sided gain survives an initial coercivity screen.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-007/judgments/chain-03.md:44:Correct. Exact transfer geometry and cascade rhetoric do not imply endpoint leverage. The chain needs an explicit bridge from the coupled-flux object to a named regularity bottleneck.
