../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-01.md:15:This is the main criticism. The original chain says to define what Tao averaging preserves or destroys, but it does not force one stable comparison level. That invites slippage between exact identities, transport statements, and bottleneck-relevant estimates. A refined version must freeze one comparison level, one observable, and one worked pass/fail pair before candidate screening begins.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-01.md:21:The attacker is right that stochastic transport, deformation observables, and pressure identities do not naturally live in the same evidentiary unit. A single flat rubric will hide mismatch rather than resolve it. The refined chain should type candidates by comparison class and only compare within a shared class.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-01.md:33:The original chain asks for prior-art notes, but not for mechanism-level overlap accounting. That is too weak. "Not already closed" is not enough if the route is functionally the same program with renamed observables. The refined chain should force explicit overlap accounting at the level of theorem mechanism, not just topic similarity.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-01.md:45:This is a serious problem. Tao sensitivity, endpoint closeness, prior-art distance, and narrowness of the first missing lemma are not naturally commensurable, and the "one primary, one secondary, one bounded negative" template biases the process toward a neat answer. The refined chain should allow zero promoted branches and should rank only within a shared architecture and gain currency.
