../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:5:The attack is mostly correct. The original chain identifies a genuinely different structural reservoir: exact stochastic transport and martingale formulas for Navier-Stokes are not interchangeable with standard Eulerian energy estimates. That is a real positive. But the attack is right that the chain delays the decisive question for too long: whether one exact stochastic observable yields coercive, localizable, endpoint-relevant control rather than an elegant reformulation.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:7:The refined branch should therefore remain live mainly as a tightly screened stochastic-mechanism audit. A positive route is still allowed, but only if it earns an explicit gain against a named blowup mechanism before Tao-comparison or endpoint packaging gets much attention.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:19:The attack is right that the original menu of stochastic objects and endpoints was too broad and too easy to backfill after the fact. It is also right that the chain should screen for non-coercivity, expectation-only content, and unusable localization much earlier. But some early freezing is still good method. The correction is not to avoid early choices; it is to freeze the blowup mechanism, candidate observable, and admissibility rules before final endpoint selection.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:24:This is a strong criticism. Exact stochastic identities are common; theorem-facing leverage is rare. The original step did not make the right discriminator explicit enough. The key test is not exactness alone, but whether the formula yields a sign, exclusion principle, monotonicity surrogate, or local/pathwise control that is genuinely more blowup-relevant than the deterministic rewrite.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:34:This is the real bottleneck, and the original chain left too much heavy lifting for it. The attack is also right that a bare martingale bound is not enough unless it controls a named concentration or stretching quantity, and that importing a stronger framework can be parasitic if it merely smuggles back the deterministic hard part.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:41:### Structural weakness 1 - representation-first rather than mechanism-first
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:44:This is the central design issue. The branch should begin by naming one singularity scenario or bad term, then asking which stochastic observable could obstruct it.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:61:### Structural weakness 5 - prior-art redundancy risk
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:64:Correct. Exact stochastic reformulation followed by nonclosure is a known failure pattern, so an explicit prior-art checkpoint is necessary before deeper investment.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:69:Correct. The issue is not only formal availability of a representation. The deeper question is whether it remains usable near the intended singular regime without relying on smooth flows, filtration assumptions, or localization/stopping constructions that collapse precisely where the branch hopes to say something.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:73:- Start with one named blowup mechanism or bad term, not a menu of stochastic formalisms.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:76:- Front-load prior-art, solution-class, stopping-time, and localization screens.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:77:- Treat local concentration exclusion as the natural first endpoint; permit continuation criteria only if the observable is already close to norm-level control.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:85:Most likely presentable result: a strong obstruction memo showing that the stochastic representation is exact but only expectation-level, non-coercive, solution-class fragile, or localized too weakly to constrain blowup.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:87:Lower-probability upside: a narrowly conditional concentration-exclusion statement tied to one specific stochastic transport observable and one named stretching or concentration mechanism.
