../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-008-judge-03.log:174:This chain is not empty. It correctly identifies a genuine structural distinction: exact stochastic transport formulas for Navier-Stokes are not the same object as standard Eulerian harmonic-analysis estimates. That is the strongest part of the chain.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-008-judge-03.log:182:This is reasonable as a scoping move, but it hides the central failure mode. The space of choices is too broad relative to the proof burden. "Stochastic Kelvin circulation," "stochastic Cauchy formula," "backward stochastic flow," and "a martingale adapted to vorticity/stretching" are not comparable objects. They live at different regularity levels, encode different information, and have different endpoint plausibility. Putting them in one menu risks wasting effort on representational variety rather than selecting the one object most likely to interact with a blowup mechanism.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-008-judge-03.log:184:The endpoint menu is also under-argued. "Continuation criterion," "local concentration exclusion," and "contradiction line for blowup concentration" are not equally reachable. A continuation criterion usually demands a norm or structural quantity with clear coercive content. Local concentration exclusion is more local and may fit stochastic transport better. A contradiction line for blowup concentration is the vaguest of the three and can absorb failure without producing real progress. As written, the step lets the researcher pick the endpoint after the fact, which biases the chain toward survivable narrative rather than the hardest honest target.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-008-judge-03.log:208:The permitted outputs are also uneven. "A martingale bound" is far too weak unless the bound controls a blowup-relevant norm or local concentration quantity. Martingale bounds are easy to write and hard to make decisive. "Conditional continuation implication" is stronger but usually unrealistic unless the prior steps already uncovered a nearly critical control mechanism. "Concentration-exclusion estimate" is the most plausible option, but the chain does not prioritize it, even though it is arguably the only endpoint naturally aligned with localized stochastic transport.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-008-judge-03.log:551:+The attack is mostly correct. The original chain identifies a genuinely different structural reservoir: exact stochastic transport and martingale formulas for Navier-Stokes are not interchangeable with standard Eulerian energy estimates. That is a real positive. But the attack is right that the chain delays the decisive question for too long: whether one exact stochastic observable yields coercive, localizable, endpoint-relevant control rather than an elegant reformulation.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-008-judge-03.log:633:+Lower-probability upside: a narrowly conditional concentration-exclusion statement tied to one specific stochastic transport observable and one named stretching or concentration mechanism.
