../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:19:The attack is right that the original menu of stochastic objects and endpoints was too broad and too easy to backfill after the fact. It is also right that the chain should screen for non-coercivity, expectation-only content, and unusable localization much earlier. But some early freezing is still good method. The correction is not to avoid early choices; it is to freeze the blowup mechanism, candidate observable, and admissibility rules before final endpoint selection.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:24:This is a strong criticism. Exact stochastic identities are common; theorem-facing leverage is rare. The original step did not make the right discriminator explicit enough. The key test is not exactness alone, but whether the formula yields a sign, exclusion principle, monotonicity surrogate, or local/pathwise control that is genuinely more blowup-relevant than the deterministic rewrite.
../../planning-runs/run-008/judgments/chain-03.md:39:The attack is right that the positive output standard needs to say where the gain sits relative to criticality and known continuation burdens, and it is right that "expectation-level gain with no pathwise or local coercive consequence" should be an explicit negative bucket. But keeping a proposition-scale conditional output is still useful if the missing lemma is genuinely narrower than the full regularity problem.
