+# Exploration 002 Goal
+
+## Objective
+
+Fix the prior-art comparator and anti-repackaging burden for the stochastic
+branch, or say plainly that the repository never built a concrete enough
+comparator packet to keep the branch alive.
+
+This exploration is responsible for:
+
+- one closest prior-art stochastic Navier-Stokes comparator;
+- one statement of what is already standard there;
+- one statement of what further gain this branch would need;
+- and one anti-repackaging rule that later steps could enforce mechanically.
+
+## Required Questions
+
+Answer all of the following from local repository materials:
+
+1. What exact stochastic comparator is actually named on disk:
+   `Constantin-Iyer`,
+   stochastic circulation more generally,
+   backward-flow / back-to-label structure,
+   or only a generic literature neighborhood?
+2. What exact gain is already standard there on the repository record?
+3. What exact beyond-baseline gain would the present branch need so that it is
+   not just replaying a known exact-but-nonclosing stochastic reformulation?
+4. Can the anti-repackaging rule be stated concretely in this branch’s own
+   burden language, especially around expectation-only control, filtration
+   bookkeeping, and imported stronger frameworks?
+5. Does the branch already fail here because the local record never gets beyond
+   comparator naming without a usable theorem-facing gap?
+
+## Working Hypotheses To Test, Not Assume
+
+- `Constantin-Iyer representation term` is the nearest explicit comparator
+  because it is the only stochastic name frozen in the planning archive.
+- The repository supports the existence of a known failure pattern
+  (`exact stochastic reformulation -> expectation/localization nonclosure`) more
+  strongly than it supports any concrete beyond-prior-art gain.
+- The right anti-repackaging rule is:
+  stochastic elegance does not count if the usable content is only the
+  deterministic burden rewritten through expectation, filtration, or imported
+  regularity machinery.
+
+Confirm, refine, or reject these hypotheses from source-backed evidence.
+
+## Success Criteria
+
+- Produce one comparator table with columns:
+  `candidate comparator`, `status`, `already standard`, `required new gain`,
+  `overlap verdict`.
+- State one anti-repackaging rule in language that Step 2 could enforce.
+- End with one explicit conclusion:
+  `baseline and gap frozen`, or
+  `prior-art / anti-repackaging obstruction already active`.
+
+## Failure Criteria
+
+- The report treats a named comparator as if that alone fixed the overlap
+  burden.
+- The report cannot say what is already standard and what would actually be new.
+- The report leaves anti-repackaging as an abstract warning rather than a kill
+  rule.
+
+If failure occurs, say so directly and recommend overlap or anti-repackaging
+obstruction.
+
+## Source Priorities
+
+Use the local repository only. High-priority anchors:
+
+- `missions/beyond-de-giorgi/steps/step-012/GOAL.md`
+- `missions/beyond-de-giorgi/CHAIN.md`
+- `missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-007/planner-chains/chain-04.md`
